Step5: Exploratory Data Analysis


The EDA approach will enable us to identify the patterns, anomalies and better insights of the data to further process with the modeling. A few of the insights we obtained are from 
  • Pair plot
  • Violin plot
  • Swarm plot
  • Box plot
 
5.1 Distribution chart:
The target variable, diagnosis has been plotted in order to identify the range of the people who are Malignant and Benign. The following chart will represent the class distribution of the target variable.

According to the chart, the number of women who are Benign: 357 and the number of women who are Malignant: 212

5.2 Pair plot:
The pair plot allows us to see both distributions of single variables and relationships between two variables.



Few variables have a linear relationship with the other features, while the rest are scattered.



5.3 Standardization:
  • Standardization rescales the data to have a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1 (unit variance).
  • Since differences between values of features are very high to observe on plot, the standardization is performed prior to the visualization.

5.4 Violin plot:
The Violin plot shows the distribution of quantitative data across several levels of one (or more) categorical variables such that those distributions can be compared.
  • The above plot is distributed for the first 10 features of the data with respect to the target variable. The features which do not overlap abundantly are considered for further analysis.
  • Secondly, the features ranging from 11-20 and 21-30 are plotted and likewise, the distribution is performed on the following features too.


5.5 Swarm plot:
Swarm plot is a good complement to a box or violin plot in cases where we want to show all observations along with some representation of the underlying distribution. Besides, this gives a better representation of the distribution of values with respect to the features involved.
  • The above chart allows us to identify the features which are distributed accordingly and not. The features with respect to target variable are invaluable for the modeling, the scattered distribution over the features are redundant. Likewise, the following analysis is performed on all the features below.                                                      
  •        In the swarm plot, the variance can be visualized clearer.
  •         area_worst in last swarm plot looks like malignant and benign are separated not totally but mostly. However smoothness_se in swarm plot 2 looks like malignant and benign are mixed it is hard to classify while using this feature.


5.6 Box plot:
  • Boxplots are a standardized way of displaying the distribution of data based on a five-number summary (“minimum”, first quartile (Q1), median, third quartile (Q3), and “maximum”).
  • In addition, the box plot is the best way of identifying outliers. However, as we are working on a medical dataset, there can be some extreme values depending on the patient's severe conditions.
  • Hence, these values must be considered and ignored the outliers.


  •      Features, concavity_worst, and concave point_worst looks similar, but to decide whether they are correlated with each other or not we perform another technique (Correlation Matrix). (Not always true but, basically if the features are correlated with each other we can drop one of them)


5.7 Correlation Matrix:

  • To identify the correlation between features, we perform the heat map i.e, Correlation matrix
  • The correlation matrix is a table showing correlation coefficients between variables. Each cell in the table shows the correlation between two variables

  • From the heat map figure we observe, radius_mean, perimeter_mean and area_mean are correlated with each other so we will use only area_mean
  • Besides, from the swarm plot as well, the area_mean looks clear. Hence we only consider area_mean
